column5: "title":"High cholesterol? CVD risk? It might be your thyroid"
column7: "caption":"Do you have high cholesterol? Are you concerned about your heart health? You might want to get your thyroid checked out. Thyroid hormones play a major role in lipid metabolism and are one of the major causes of high cholesterol. Read on to learn more."
column8: "description":"\u003Cp\u003EI\u0026rsquo;ve written enough articles on thyroid health to fill an entire \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/thyroid\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Ee-book\u003C\/a\u003E: all about \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/low-t3-syndrome-i-its-not-about-the-thyroid\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Elow T3 syndrome\u003C\/a\u003E
column9: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/5-thyroid-patterns-that-wont-show-up-on-standard-lab-tests\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Efive thyroid patterns\u003C\/a\u003E that won\u0026rsquo;t show up on standard lab tests
column11: and the \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/the-thyroid-gut-connection\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Egut\u0026ndash;thyroid connection\u003C\/a\u003E.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThyroid hormone regulates a great deal of metabolism
column12: and virtually every cell in the body has a receptor for thyroid hormone. In a \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/functional-medicine-approach-to-high-cholesterol\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Erecent podcast\u003C\/a\u003E
column13: I mentioned poor thyroid function as one of the six underlying causes of high cholesterol. In this article
column14: I\u0026rsquo;ll discuss exactly how your thyroid impacts lipid metabolism
column16: and other risk factors for cardiovascular disease. First
column18: a quick review of the major hormones involved.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA quick review of thyroid physiology and lab panels\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid is a small butterfly-shaped gland that sits at the front of the neck. It receives a hormone signal from the pituitary and secretes other hormones into the bloodstream. You might be familiar with these hormones
column19: which are included in a full thyroid panel:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH):\u003C\/strong\u003E This hormone is released by the pituitary gland and reflects the body\u0026rsquo;s \u003Cem\u003Eneed\u003C\/em\u003E for thyroid hormone. This means that when TSH is high
column20: not enough thyroid hormone is being produced (hypothyroidism). When TSH is low
column21: there is more than enough thyroid hormone in the body (hyperthyroidism).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroxine (T4):\u003C\/strong\u003E The thyroid gland releases large amounts of this largely inactive form of thyroid hormone
column22: which must be converted into the more active T3 by deiodinase enzymes. Low amounts of T4 may indicate hypothyroidism; high amounts may indicate hyperthyroidism.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriiodothyronine (T3):\u003C\/strong\u003E This is the active form of thyroid hormone
column23: secreted in small amounts by the thyroid gland and formed from the conversion of T4 to T3. T3 is the primary thyroid hormone that will act on cells all over the body to regulate metabolism. Low amounts of T3 may indicate hypothyroidism or \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/low-t3-syndrome-i-its-not-about-the-thyroid\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Elow T3 syndrome\u003C\/a\u003E; high amounts indicate hyperthyroidism.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIf thyroid medication is given for hypothyroidism
column24: it is usually in the form of T4
column26: or a combination of the two.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe association between thyroid hormone levels and cholesterol\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe association between thyroid function and cholesterol has been known for quite some time. As early as 1934
column27: it was recognized that \u0026ldquo;the concentration of blood cholesterol is usually raised in hypothyroidism
column28: and lowered slightly in hyperthyroidism\u0026rdquo; (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/16694228\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E1\u003C\/a\u003E). Today
column29: a PubMed search for thyroid and cholesterol yields more than 3
column32: are aware of how various thyroid conditions can impact cholesterol levels.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ELet\u0026rsquo;s review the four major types and how they impact basic cholesterol measurements:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism: \u003C\/strong\u003EPeople with an underactive thyroid
column34: often have increased levels of total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/8283927\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E2\u003C\/a\u003E) and may have elevated triglyceride levels as well (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/15010297\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E3\u003C\/a\u003E). Thyroid medication can significantly improve lipid profiles. A study in newly diagnosed hypothyroid patients found that total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol levels decreased after T4 treatment. Those with higher TSH levels (indicating a greater \u003Cem\u003Eneed \u003C\/em\u003Efor thyroid hormone and a greater degree of hypothyroidism) at baseline saw a more dramatic reduction in cholesterol levels with T4 therapy (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/2327707\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E4\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubclinical hypothyroidism:\u003C\/strong\u003E Subclinical hypothyroidism (SH) is characterized by elevated serum TSH with normal levels of free T4 and free T3. Subclinical hypothyroidism is far more common than overt hypothyroidism and may affect up to 9 percent of the population (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/10695693\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E5\u003C\/a\u003E). Studies are mixed on the effect of\u0026nbsp;subclinical hypothyroidism on lipid profiles
column35: but even within the normal range of values
column36: increasing TSH is associated with an increase in total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/11932277\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E6\u003C\/a\u003E
column37: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/12097204\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E7\u003C\/a\u003E). One systematic review found that T4 substitution therapy on average resulted in an eight mg\/dL decrease in total cholesterol and a 10 mg\/dL decrease in LDL cholesterol in people with\u0026nbsp;subclinical hypothyroidism (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/10999775\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E8\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid autoimmunity:\u003C\/strong\u003E Autoimmunity is a major cause of hypothyroidism. An estimated 90 percent of people with underactive thyroid have autoimmune thyroiditis
column38: also known as Hashimoto\u0026rsquo;s disease. People with high-normal TSH levels that have positive anti-thyroid antibodies are even more likely to have abnormal cholesterol levels. On the bright side
column39: their cholesterol levels are more likely to respond to thyroid medication (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/9506856\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E9\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism: \u003C\/strong\u003EWhile not as common
column40: hyperthyroidism is associated with low levels of total cholesterol
column43: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/7067079\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E11\u003C\/a\u003E). While this may seem like a good thing
column44: low blood cholesterol has been associated with altered cell membrane function
column50: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/12967690\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E14\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHow the thyroid regulates lipid metabolism\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFair warning
column51: this section contains the nitty gritty details of lipid metabolism. If you\u0026rsquo;re not in the mood for a physiology lesson
column52: you can skip on to the next section!\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones regulate cholesterol synthesis\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EYou may have heard that dietary cholesterol \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/the-diet-heart-myth-cholesterol-and-saturated-fat-are-not-the-enemy\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Edoesn\u0026rsquo;t have much impact\u003C\/a\u003E on blood levels of cholesterol. This is because cholesterol is also synthesized by the liver. This process is tightly regulated by several hormones
column53: including thyroid hormones. TSH increases the expression and activity of an enzyme called HMG CoA reductase
column54: which controls the rate of cholesterol synthesis (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pmc\/articles\/PMC4409286\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E15\u003C\/a\u003E). This means that hypothyroidism increases the amount of cholesterol produced in the liver. This cholesterol is then packaged with triglycerides into VLDL particles
column55: which are shipped out to the bloodstream.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones affect lipoprotein lipase (LPL)\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EVLDL particles travel through the bloodstream until they reach the small blood vessel beds
column56: where they encounter an enzyme called lipoprotein lipase (LPL). This enzyme breaks down the triglycerides in the VLDL particle into fatty acids
column57: which are taken up by adipose
column59: and muscle cells. T3 stimulates LPL to increase this breakdown of triglyceride-rich VLDL (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/15284087\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E16\u003C\/a\u003E). Eventually
column60: the cholesterol content of the lipoprotein becomes higher than the triglyceride content
column61: and these particles become LDL.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones increase LDL particle uptake\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ELDL particles circulate around in the blood until they bind to LDL receptors. This binding triggers the capturing of LDL particles into the cell. There
column62: the LDL particles are degraded and the contents used for cell membrane structure or converted to other steroid hormones. Through several mechanisms
column63: T3 increases the expression of LDL receptors (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/9712728\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E17\u003C\/a\u003E
column64: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/12829694\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E18\u003C\/a\u003E). This reduces the amount of time that LDL particles spend circulating in the blood and the total number of LDL particles in the blood.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones affect LDL particle oxidation\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EExcess LDL particles in the blood can cause some particles to \u0026ldquo;crash\u0026rdquo; into the blood vessel wall and be taken into the inner lining of the blood vessel. Once there
column65: the LDL particles can become oxidized
column66: which triggers inflammation and is thought to be the major event initiating the formation of arterial plaque. T3 acts as a free radical scavenger and may protect LDL from oxidation (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/15283976\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E19\u003C\/a\u003E). However
column67: high free T4 can also enhance LDL oxidation (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/9598831\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E20\u003C\/a\u003E). Thus
column68: both hypo- and hyperthyroidism can lead to LDL oxidation.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe dangers of statins in people with thyroid dysfunction\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIf you\u0026rsquo;ve been following my work for a while
column69:
you probably know my opinion of statin drugs. Here are just a few of the articles I’ve written on statins:

  • The truth about statin drugs
  • What the media isn’t telling you about statin drug trials
  • The diet–heart myth: statins don’t save lives in people without heart disease

But it turns out that statin use is particularly concerning when the cause of high cholesterol is poor thyroid function. This is due to the effects of statins on creatine kinase levels.

Creatine kinase (CK) is an enzyme expressed in many different tissues throughout the body
column70: though it\u0026rsquo;s probably most well-known for its action in muscle cells. CK is responsible for adding a phosphate to creatine to form phosphocreatine
column71: which serves as an energy reservoir and allows for the quick release of energy in times of need.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBoth statins and hypothyroidism result in CK release into the blood
column72: and the cumulative effect is severe CK elevation (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/16723812\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E21\u003C\/a\u003E
column73: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.jstage.jst.go.jp\/article\/endocrj\/53\/3\/53_3_401\/_article\/-char\/ja\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E22\u003C\/a\u003E). This can potentially amplify the adverse side effects of statins. Statins can cause a variety of skeletal muscle problems
column74: including damage and inflammation to the muscle. Based on several case reports
column75: researchers have speculated that the use of lipid-lowering agents in hypothyroid patients may severely increase the risk of myopathy and rhabdomyolysis (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pmc\/articles\/PMC4404889\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E23\u003C\/a\u003E
column77: in reviewing the relevant medical records of 77 patients treated receiving statins in a hospital
column78: a team of medical researchers discovered that only 23 percent of patients had received a thyroid panel before beginning statin treatment. Worse yet
column79: 12 percent of patients with overt hypothyroidism received statins without receiving a thyroid panel or hypothyroid diagnosis (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/16723812\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E21\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe authors commented on their findings
column80: emphasizing the need for routine thyroid screening in patients with lipid abnormalities:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u0026ldquo;We must not begin and continue to use these drugs without checking the possibility of hypothyroidism.\u0026rdquo;\u003C\/em\u003E (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/16723812\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E21\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EStatin drug information in Japan and the UK now includes warnings that emphasize the need for careful use in patients with hypothyroidism. The same cannot be said for the United States or in other countries. Thus
column81: it\u0026rsquo;s very important to exclude other diseases that cause high cholesterol
column85: before even \u003Cem\u003Econsidering\u003C\/em\u003E taking a statin.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetter markers of cardiovascular risk\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWait
column86: but I thought cholesterol tests were out\u0026mdash;aren\u0026rsquo;t lipoprotein particle numbers what we really care about?\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EYep. I\u0026rsquo;ve discussed in \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/the-diet-heart-myth-why-everyone-should-know-their-ldl-particle-number\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Eseveral articles\u003C\/a\u003E and on \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/functional-medicine-approach-to-high-cholesterol\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Emy podcast\u003C\/a\u003E why \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/what-causes-elevated-ldl-particle-number\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Elipoprotein particle numbers\u003C\/a\u003E are much better predictors of cardiovascular risk than cholesterol levels. However
column87: there are few studies that have assessed the effects of thyroid hormones on lipoprotein particle number
column88: compared to the number of studies that have assessed standard cholesterol measurements. Still
column89: we see similar effects:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELDL particle number (LDL-P): \u003C\/strong\u003ESubclinical hypothyroidism\u0026nbsp;has been associated with higher levels of ApoB-100
column90:
a surrogate marker for LDL particle number. T4 treatment significantly reduced ApoB-100 levels (25).
  • Oxidized LDL: Decreased thyroid function increases the number of LDL particles and promotes LDL “oxidizability” (26).

    • Thyroid health also impacts other cardiovascular risk factors:

    • Blood pressure: Underactive thyroid is strongly associated with hypertension. This is due to both sympathetic and adrenal activation (27). One study of 30 patients with both hypothyroidism and hypertension found that hypertension was reversed in 50 percent of patients after thyroid medication therapy (28).
    • C-reactive protein (CRP): CRP
column92: has been shown to be negatively correlated with levels of free T4 (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/14709351\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E29\u003C\/a\u003E). Patients with subclinical hypothyroidism have also been found to have increased CRP (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/14709351\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E30\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoprotein(a) (Lp(a)): \u003C\/strong\u003ELp(a) is a measure of how many lipoprotein particles are carrying apolipoprotein A1. Apolipoprotein A1 has a high affinity for oxidized lipids and is thought to be largely based on genetics. Patients with overt hypothyroidism and\u0026nbsp;subclinical hypothyroidism have increased Lp(a) (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/11041458\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E31\u003C\/a\u003E
column93: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/8421075\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E32\u003C\/a\u003E). Some studies of\u0026nbsp;subclinical hypothyroidism patients suggest that thyroid medication can reduce Lp(a) (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/14565632\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E33\u003C\/a\u003E)
column94: but others found no significant change (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/11932277\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E34\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhospholipase A\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C\/sub\u003E (Lp-PLA\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C\/sub\u003E): \u003C\/strong\u003EThis is an enzyme that travels largely with LDL particles
column96: and is involved in the development of atherosclerosis (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/15731492\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E35\u003C\/a\u003E). Subclinical hypothyroidism subjects have been shown to have higher Lp-PLA\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C\/sub\u003E (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/11036120\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E36\u003C\/a\u003E).\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomocysteine: \u003C\/strong\u003EHypothyroidism is associated with increased plasma homocysteine levels (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/11223442\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E37)\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin resistance and BMI:\u003C\/strong\u003E Insulin resistance and a high BMI are both positively correlated with low thyroid function (\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/18279023\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003E38\u003C\/a\u003E
column97:
39).

Conclusion

I hope I have convinced you that thyroid function plays a major role in lipid metabolism. I can’t tell you the number of patients I have seen in my clinic with lipid abnormalities that had undiagnosed thyroid conditions. Restoring thyroid health by correcting nutrient deficiencies
column99: and \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/why-changing-your-diet-is-always-the-first-step-in-treating-hashimotos\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Emaking simple diet and lifestyle changes\u003C\/a\u003E can often make a major difference in cholesterol levels and cardiovascular risk markers. In some cases
column100: \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/chriskresser.com\/why-thyroid-medication-is-often-necessary\/\u0022 target=\u0022_blank\u0022 rel=\u0022noopener\u0022\u003Ethyroid support in the form of medication\u003C\/a\u003E may also be helpful and is much less harmful than statins.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENow I\u0026rsquo;d like to hear from you. Do you have cardiovascular risk factors? When was the last time you had a full thyroid panel? Did you know about the thyroid\u0026ndash;cholesterol connection? Share your thoughts in the comments below.\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E"

"description":"

Children and adolescent mental health issues in today's society are increasing at an alarming rate. Our mental health professionals specialize in children’s mental health issues and provide the services you need to protect your child’s emotional well-being. Timely assessments identify problems areas and inform interventions that include counseling and behavioral approaches for patients and their families to develop ways to understand and deal with trying times.

column137: "description":"The Government\u2019s new mental health green paper has announced new funding for mental health support in schools
column138: including the development and training of senior mental health leads to work in schools from 2019. Greenwood Academy in Birmingham appointed Sean Jordan as its own senior youth and mental health worker three years ago
column139: and they haven\u2019t looked back. Here
column140: Sean and Assistant Headteacher Laurence Cole explain Greenwood\u2019s approach to mental health and student support."
column156: we appointed Sean as our youth and mental health worker \u2013 a senior position that forms the central focus of all our work around mental health. Sean has responsibility for the students with social
column157: emotional and mental health issues and children with ADHD
column158: and he also coordinates all outside agency support
column161: family support services and addiction services.\n\nWe arrange for all at-risk students to take a mental health questionnaire
column162: which is specifically designed to identify students who may have high anxiety and\/or depression. We then roll out the Pupil Attitudes to Self and School (PASS) assessment to all of our students.\n\nPASS is 20 minute psychometric tool designed to highlight students\u2019 feelings about themselves as learners and their feelings about school. The results
column163: which are grouped into nine factors linked to educational goals (such as self-regard as a learner
column164: confidence in learning and attitudes to attendance)
column165: enable us to build a complete picture of a student\u2019s motivation
column166: attitude and engagement at school. The results are standardised so we can also see how our scores compare to the national average."

column120: "description":"The self-administered questionnaire is an ideal screening device for identifying non-psychotic and minor psychiatric disorders to help inform further intervention\nGHQ is available in four different versions
column121: enabling researchers and clinicians to select the version most appropriate to their individual requirements\nFor researchers intending to set-up their own localised validation studies \u2013 the GHQ User\u2019s Guide provides guidance and advise"
column137: "description":"The Government\u2019s new mental health green paper has announced new funding for mental health support in schools
column138: including the development and training of senior mental health leads to work in schools from 2019. Greenwood Academy in Birmingham appointed Sean Jordan as its own senior youth and mental health worker three years ago
column139: and they haven\u2019t looked back. Here
column140: Sean and Assistant Headteacher Laurence Cole explain Greenwood\u2019s approach to mental health and student support."
column156: we appointed Sean as our youth and mental health worker \u2013 a senior position that forms the central focus of all our work around mental health. Sean has responsibility for the students with social
column157: emotional and mental health issues and children with ADHD
column158: and he also coordinates all outside agency support
column161: family support services and addiction services.\n\nWe arrange for all at-risk students to take a mental health questionnaire
column162: which is specifically designed to identify students who may have high anxiety and\/or depression. We then roll out the Pupil Attitudes to Self and School (PASS) assessment to all of our students.\n\nPASS is 20 minute psychometric tool designed to highlight students\u2019 feelings about themselves as learners and their feelings about school. The results
column163: which are grouped into nine factors linked to educational goals (such as self-regard as a learner
column164: confidence in learning and attitudes to attendance)
column165: enable us to build a complete picture of a student\u2019s motivation
column166: attitude and engagement at school. The results are standardised so we can also see how our scores compare to the national average."
column181: "description":"PASS has given us a good indication about where our students\u2019 barriers might lie \u2013 and big barriers are their self-regard as a learner and perceived learning capability.\n\nAnxiety is a big area of concern across our student population. It will always be there
column183: but a lot of work is done to lower students\u2019 anxiety levels so they don\u2019t work themselves up. When they leave in Year 11
column184: we want them to gain good GCSEs and get through the process without much anxiety.\n\nTo take just one example
column185: we\u2019re working with a student at the moment who has low scores on the self-regard and perceived learning capability factors \u2013 but she\u2019s attended 40 extra lessons this term already so is clearly putting in the effort. However
column186: she still doesn\u2019t think she\u2019s doing enough and is heaping far too much pressure on herself."
